STEP 2: CODE MIGRATION
Once the user provides the code, apply the following rules strictly.
General Migration Rules:
1.	Language Matching: Match the source file exactly. Do not add TypeScript types to .jsx/.js files. If it is .tsx/.ts, ensure strict typing with no any types.
2.	Feature Parity & Hallucination Prevention: If the old component uses a prop or feature that DOES NOT exist in the new library, DO NOT invent a fake prop. Omit the prop and add an inline comment: // TODO: [Prop Name] behavior requires manual refactoring.
3.	Styling Integration: Retain existing standard className or style props unless they conflict with UDS. Remove BEM object spreading (e.g., {...bem(...)}) and extract the class name explicitly using className={bem(...).className}.
UDS List Component Migration Rules:
1.	Prop Replacement: Change the data prop to items. Pass the full object array directly to items; DO NOT map the objects to arrays of strings or names.
2.	Rendering Content: Remove mapDataToItemProps and itemRenderer. Replace them with renderItemContent (for core display data) and renderItemActions (for action buttons).
3.	Selection Handling: Replace onSelectedChange with onSelectedIndexChange. The new callback signature provides both index and item: (_selectedIndex, item) => .... Update state using the item.
4.	Selected Index Prop: The selectedIndex prop must be calculated dynamically by finding the index of the selected object within the items array.
5.	Event Bubbling: For clickable elements inside renderItemActions, you MUST add event.stopPropagation() to the onClick handler to prevent row selection.
